            5 tried-and-tested ways to deliver delightful UX (and impress your
            customers)
          </h1>
          <p>
            Here are five ways to analyze, understand, and optimize your website
            UX to create better user experiences.
          </p>
          <h1 style="font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px; font-weight: bold">
            1. Learn what users <i>actually</i> do on your site
          </h1>
          <p>
            The first step to improving your users‚Äô experience on your site is
            to understand how they currently experience it. After all,
            <strong
              >the best way to connect with your visitors is to empathize with
              them</strong
            >.
          </p>
          <p>
            <a href="">Heatmaps</a> are visual representations of where users
            scroll, click, tap, and engage‚Äîor don‚Äôt. (And they‚Äôre free forever
            with <mark style="background-color: #fde293">Hotjar</mark>!) Use
            them to quickly identify
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li>üëÄ Which page elements capture user attention</li>
            <li>‚¨áÔ∏è How far down your pages users scroll</li>
            <li>üò† Areas of frustration</li>
            <li>üì±How mobile and desktop versions of your site compare</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            Then, turn those insights into action and implement data-driven UX
            improvements that make a real impact.
          </p>
          <p>
            Even better: combine heatmaps with other insight-providing
            tools‚Äîlike session recordings, feedback widgets, web analytics, and
            A/B tests‚Äîto get even more in-depth knowledge of how and why site
            visitors behave the way they do.
          </p>
          <h1 style="font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px; font-weight: bold">
            2. Team up with other customer-facing teams to get the full story
          </h1>
          <p>
            Each team has its own micro-goals, but every team shares the same
            macro-goal:
            <strong
              >to create better experiences for your users so they‚Äôll convert
              and stick around</strong
            >. So why not pool your resources to get a full 360-view of user
            behavior?
          </p>
          <p>Depending on your company culture, try these strategies:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              Host <a href="">Watch Parties</a> where teams come together to
              review recordings of real user sessions related to a specific goal
            </li>
            <li>Sit in on existing research projects run by other teams</li>
            <li>
              Send regular updates about your customer learnings in a shared
              Slack channel
            </li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            By sharing insights across all teams that collect customer
            knowledge‚Äîlike marketing, UX, sales, data, and customer
            success‚Äîevery team is empowered to make better decisions that
            improve your user‚Äôs experience at each stage of their website
            journey.
          </p>
          <p>
            üí° Pro tip: Jennifer Dorman, Head of User Insights at Babbel, and
            Paula Herrera, UX Research Team Lead at
            <mark style="background-color: #fde293">Hotjar</mark>,
            <a href="">sing the praises</a> of shared knowledge repositories,
            like insight hubs on valuable topics that every team can access.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
