          <h1 style="font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px; font-weight: bold">
            3. Examine your failures (or even better: learn from ours)
          </h1>
          <p>
            We‚Äôve all been there. Even when improving the customer experience is
            at the very heart of what you do‚Äîmistakes can happen.
          </p>
          <p>
            Instead of trying to sweep them under the rug while whistling
            nonchalantly and hoping nobody noticed anything,
            <strong
              >take a good look at your failures and examine what went
              wrong</strong
            >. Why didn‚Äôt your latest campaign, landing page, or feature launch
            perform the way you‚Äôd hoped? And what can you do better next time?
          </p>
          <p>
            üí° Want some inspiration?
            <a href="">Here are seven UX fails we made so you don‚Äôt have to</a>
            (and how we turned them into wins).
          </p>
          <h1 style="font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px; font-weight: bold">
            4. Get more from your A/B tests
          </h1>
          <p>
            A/B tests are a great way to get solid data about how different
            website elements‚Äîlike button placement, copy length, and customer
            testimonials‚Äîaffect user behavior‚Ä¶and conversions. But that data
            only tells you which versions users preferred, not why they
            preferred them.
          </p>
          <p>
            To understand why your winning pages won, use product experience
            insights tools like
            <a href="">heatmaps and session recordings</a> to dig into user
            behavior on each variant. By seeing exactly which parts of the page
            your users liked (and didn‚Äôt), you can replicate your success for
            future campaigns.
          </p>
          <h1 style="font-size: 22px; line-height: 24px; font-weight: bold">
            5. Ask users what they want (what they really, really want)
          </h1>
          <p>
            One of the best ways to improve people‚Äôs experiences on your website
            is to use always-on surveys or feedback widgets to ask them, ‚ÄúHow
            can we improve our website?‚Äù and then implement their feedback.
          </p>
          <p>
            <strong
              >If you‚Äôre not surveying your users, you‚Äôre missing out on a
              wealth of insights and opportunities for quick wins</strong
            >. Obviously, we don‚Äôt recommend changing everything just because
            one person said so, but if you see the same feedback responses again
            and again, it‚Äôs probably a sign that you need to listen to the voice
            of the customer.
          </p>
          <p>
            üí°Pro tip: to make it even easier and faster to get actionable
            insights,
            <a href="">leverage AI to create goal-oriented survey questions</a>,
            so you can pinpoint exactly which UX improvements to make next.
          </p>
